<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14150">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Railroading.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10266">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do THREE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10266 mb-requirement-id-10267">
        (a) Name three types of modern freight trains. Explain why unit trains
        are more efficient than mixed freight trains. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/E0m9Nu1pvy8" target="_blank"
          >Types of Freight Trains (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10266 mb-requirement-id-10268">
        (b) Name one Class I or regional railroad. Explain what major cities it
        serves, the locations of major terminals, service facilities, and crew
        change points, and the major commodities it carries. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://emaqualityindustries.com/class-i-railroads-in-usa/"
          target="_blank"
          >Class I Railroads in USA: What Are They, History, and Why Do They
          Matter (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://experience.arcgis.com/experience/b6c12fd0a4774f38a303e3d034775854/"
          target="_blank"
          >FRA Rail Network (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10266 mb-requirement-id-10269">
        (c) Using models or pictures, identify 10 types of railroad freight or
        passenger cars. Explain the purpose of each type of car. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/psjExhXfvbI" target="_blank"
          >Every Type of Railcar Explained in 15 Minutes (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.bnsf.com/about-bnsf/virtual-train-tour/"
          target="_blank"
          >Virtual Train Tour (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10266 mb-requirement-id-10270">
        (d) Explain how a modern diesel or electric locomotive develops power.
        Explain the terms dynamic braking and radial steering trucks. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/nGhBHrr5CYQ" target="_blank"
          >Why Locomotives Don't Have Tires (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/dCQ9Wi8PlYY" target="_blank"
          >Dynamic Braking | Diesel Electric Locomotives | Regenerative Braking
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/aW3P9mTv0Jk" target="_blank"
          >[Rail Insights] Take a Closer Look at the Wheel-Rail-Interface
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10271">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10271 mb-requirement-id-10272">
        (a) Explain the purpose and formation of Amtrak. Explain, by the use of
        a timetable, a plan for making a trip by rail between two cities at
        least 500 miles apart. List the times of departure and arrival at your
        destination, the train number and name, and the type of service you
        want. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/oRoxy8pMqLo" target="_blank"
          >The History of Amtrak in 2 Minutes (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/anKNW1YHBoU" target="_blank"
          >Amtrak Map USA: Understand America's Train Routes (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.amtrak.com/plan-your-trip.html?intcmp=wsp_hp-trip-planning_link_start-planning_slide1"
          target="_blank"
          >Trip Planning Map (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.amtrak.com/train-schedules-timetables"
          target="_blank"
          >Amtrak Schedules &amp; Timetables (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10271 mb-requirement-id-10273">
        (b) List and explain the various forms of public/mass transit using
        rail. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/fSgMi57YbDM" target="_blank"
          >Every Transit System That Works Explained in 9 Minutes (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10274">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10274 mb-requirement-id-10275">
        (a) Name four departments of a railroad company. Describe what each
        department does. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.managementlegend.com/what-is-rail-operations-management/"
          target="_blank"
          >What Is Rail Operations Management (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/q6WM65grTMs" target="_blank"
          >MOW—Maintenance of Way (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://splives.org/the-southern-pacific-story/"
          target="_blank"
          >Departments—Pull Down Menu Under The Southern Pacific Story
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10274 mb-requirement-id-10276">
        (b) Tell about the opportunities in railroading that interest you most
        and why. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://aslrra.org/about-us/career-opportunities/"
          target="_blank"
          >Why Work for a Short Line or Regional Railroad? (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/8ofUGMZCRH8" target="_blank"
          >Railroad Careers: Conductors (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/4w4j1tESxXk" target="_blank"
          >Metro Careers—Operations (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/f4loypZNHeY" target="_blank"
          >Union Pacific—Train Crew (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/n1clZI-RZGc" target="_blank"
          >A Day in the Life of an Amtrak Conductor (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/AN4QWTNKicM" target="_blank"
          >Amtrak Police Department Careers (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/cRDQ8PM4Y3Y" target="_blank"
          >Amtrak On Board Services Jobs (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10274 mb-requirement-id-10277">
        (c) Name four rail support industries. Describe the function of each
        one. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/anJUiOLMGpk" target="_blank"
          >How Millions of Meters of Train Rails Are Made From Steel - Railroad
          Tracks Mass Production Line (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/h8nddK1NZSk" target="_blank"
          >Inside the Massive Factory Where Siemens Builds Trains (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/D_xJmt50LtQ" target="_blank"
          >Track Inspections: Keeping Railroads Safe in Under 5 Minutes
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9XiBZofqFIM" target="_blank"
          >Railway Freight Services (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/YYfxo2otxCw" target="_blank"
          >Why Chicago's Rail Hub Is So Vital to the National Economy | WSJ
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10274 mb-requirement-id-10278">
        (d) With your parent or guardian's and counselor's approval, interview
        someone employed in the rail industry. Learn what that person does and
        how this person became interested in railroading. Find out what type of
        schooling and training is required for this position. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Mqo0IsStelk" target="_blank"
          >The Informational Interview: Researching a Career (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10307">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10307 mb-requirement-id-10309">
        (a) Explain the purpose of Operation Lifesaver and its mission. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/PVCVqdwj9QI" target="_blank"
          >Be Safe—Always Expect a Train (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10307 mb-requirement-id-10310">
        (b) List 9 track basic safety tips to remember when you are around a
        railroad track. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/DXubsyGnJYA" target="_blank"
          >Railroad Safety—Do's and Don'ts (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics"
          target="_blank"
          >Track Safety Basics (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.mass.gov/doc/srts-railroad-crossing-safety-flyer-english/download"
          target="_blank"
          >See Train Tracks Ahead? Know What To Do (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10307 mb-requirement-id-10311">
        (c) List 9 safety considerations that should be followed when walking
        near a railroad track. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.floridarail.com/news/railroad-safety-9-facts-to-keep-you-safe-near-the-tracks-and-avoid-train-accidents/"
          target="_blank"
          >Railroad Safety—9 Facts to Keep You Safe Near the Tracks and Avoid
          Train Accidents (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/zsReiSJw0SI" target="_blank"
          >The Dangers of Taking Photos on Train Tracks (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10307 mb-requirement-id-10312">
        (d) Tell your counselor what a driver can do to safely operate near
        tracks. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/driving-safely-near-tracks"
          target="_blank"
          >Driving Safely Near Tracks (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10307 mb-requirement-id-10313">
        (e) Explain safety precautions when using a light rail or commuter
        train. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_gxTH8U4cu4" target="_blank"
          >Tracks and Transit—Safety in Passenger Rail Systems (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/GAfugEgV9cI" target="_blank"
          >Safety Around Streetcars and Light Rail (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10279">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Explain the appearance and meaning of the following rail signs and
      signals: <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a
        href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics/rail-signs-and-signals"
        target="_blank"
        >Rail Signs and Signals (website)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10280">
        (a) Passive signs and active signs <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.nationalssc.com/the-importance-of-railroad-crossing-signs"
          target="_blank"
          >The 2 Types of Railroad Crossing Signs (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10281">
        (b) Devices at the crossing (flashing red lights—with or without bells,
        flashing red lights and gates, and cantilever flashing lights) <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/hyTCBIjla6M" target="_blank"
          >Rail Crossing Types From Safety Perspectives (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics/rail-signs-and-signals/devices-crossing"
          target="_blank"
          >Devices at the Crossing (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10282">
        (c) Markings on the road (pavement markings and stop bars) <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics/rail-signs-and-signals/markings-road"
          target="_blank"
          >Markings on the Road (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10283">
        (d) Signs before the crossing (advance warning sign, advance warning
        sign for side streets, no train horn sign, and low ground clearance
        grade crossing sign) <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics/rail-signs-and-signals/signs-crossing"
          target="_blank"
          >Signs Before the Crossing (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10284">
        (e) Signs along the railroad property (no trespassing sign) <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://oli.org/safety-near-trains/track-safety-basics/rail-signs-and-signals/signs-along-railroad-property"
          target="_blank"
          >Signs Along Railroad Property (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10279 mb-requirement-id-10285">
        (f) Signs at the crossing (crossbuck sign, emergency notification system
        sign, multiple track sign, stop sign, and yield sign) <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/AaGx08xfmu4" target="_blank"
          >Why Are There 2 Railroad Crossing Signs? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10287">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Do EACH of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10287 mb-requirement-id-10288">
        (a) Explain how railroad signals operate and show two basic signal types
        using color or configuration. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9kRJPSVdzlM" target="_blank"
          >How Railroad Crossings Work (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Q1UlOEUdows" target="_blank"
          >How To Read Railroad Signals (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10287 mb-requirement-id-10289">
        (b) Explain the meaning of three horn signals. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/eI6xSjkcXTY" target="_blank"
          >How Trains Talk to Each Other | Horn Sounds | Train Safety (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.up.com/news/safety/tr101620-train-safety-horns-signals"
          target="_blank"
          >Railroad Safety: Train Horns and Grade Crossing Signals (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10287 mb-requirement-id-10290">
        (c) Describe a way to signal a train for an emergency stop. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.wikihow.com/Stop-a-Train-in-an-Emergency"
          target="_blank"
          >How To Stop a Train in an Emergency (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10287 mb-requirement-id-10291">
        (d) Explain the use and function of the EOTD (end-of-train device), or
        FRED (flashing rear end device), used on the last car of most freight
        trains. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://www.american-rails.com/etd.html" target="_blank"
          >The End-of-Train Device (EOTD) and Its Impact on Railroading
          (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/lz0Q646DUL0" target="_blank"
          >End of Train Device (EOTD) or Flashing Rear End Device (FRED)
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10292">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Do ONE of the following special-interest options:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10292 mb-requirement-id-10293">
        (a) <strong>Option A—Model Railroading.</strong> With your parent or
        guardian's and counselor's approval, do TWO of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10295">
        (1) Draw a layout of your own model railroad or one that could be built
        in your home. Design a point-to-point track or loop with different
        routings. Include one of the following: turnaround or terminal or yard
        or siding. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-2-layout-planning"
          target="_blank"
          >Layout Planning (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/oJL8DZO5mks" target="_blank"
          >Model Railroad Layout Design for Beginners (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://stanshobbiesandinterests.com/2025/09/24/five-starter-track-plans-that-make-model-railroading-fun/"
          target="_blank"
          >Five Starter Track Plans That Make Model Railroading Fun (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10296">
        (2) Build one model railroad car kit or one locomotive kit. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://www.nmra.org/beginner/safety" target="_blank"
          >Modeling Safety (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://midwestmodelrr.com/blog/model-railroading-safety-and-etiquette/"
          target="_blank"
          >Model Railroading Safety and Etiquette (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-11-tools"
          target="_blank"
          >Tools (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10297">
        (3) Name the scale of four popular model railroad gauges. Identify the
        scale of four model cars or locomotives. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/b5lk_2ROlD0" target="_blank"
          >Comparing Model Train Scales: T, Z, N, Tt, Ho, S, O, G Scales
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10298">
        (4) Locate the website of four model railroad - related manufacturers or
        magazine publishers. Print information on their products and services
        and discuss the information with your counselor.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10299">
        (5) Build one railroad structure (from scratch or using a kit), paint
        and weather the structure, mount it on your layout or diorama, and make
        the surrounding area on the diorama scenic. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/h0xQB2J2HKg" target="_blank"
          >Weather Plastic Kit Buildings Easy—Detailed Guide DIY (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-7-structures"
          target="_blank"
          >Structures (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-10-weathering"
          target="_blank"
          >Weathering (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10300">
        (6) Alone or with others, build a model railroad or modular layout
        including ballast and scenery. Make electrical connections and operate a
        train. Describe what you enjoyed most. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9uzOOMTzDAw" target="_blank"
          >How To Ballast Your Track—Model Railway Basics: Episode Six
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-6-scenery"
          target="_blank"
          >Scenery (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10301">
        (7) Participate in a switching contest on a timesaver layout and record
        your time. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/7LdHlfPOB6o" target="_blank"
          >Fun With Model Train Switching Puzzles (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/I0De0mAFJWQ" target="_blank"
          >Switching Puzzle—Timesaver (Timelapse) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.wymann.info/ShuntingPuzzles/sw-timesaver.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Classic Switching Puzzles — John Allen's Timesaver (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10293 mb-requirement-id-10294">
        (8) Explain the difference between powering and controlling a model
        railroad by using direct current, and powering and controlling a model
        railroad using digital command control. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/q5WeBPPPq_I" target="_blank"
          >Differences Between DC and DCC HO Locomotives (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/z5TiK_Ay-0g" target="_blank"
          >DC vs. DCC: What's Best for Your Model Railroad?! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nmra.org/beginners-guide-part-5-adding-power"
          target="_blank"
          >Adding Power (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10292 mb-requirement-id-10302">
        (b) <strong>Option B—Railfanning.</strong> With your parent or
        guardian's and counselor's approval, do TWO of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10302 mb-requirement-id-10303">
        (1) Visit a railroad museum, historical display, or a prototype railroad
        sponsored public event. With permission, photograph, digitally record,
        or sketch items of interest. Explain what you saw and describe your
        photos, sketches, or video. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://whichmuseum.com/place/united-states-2682?q=railroad"
          target="_blank"
          >Railroading Museums in the US (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jaU7xtVQBPM" target="_blank"
          >Railroad Museum Etiquette (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10302 mb-requirement-id-10304">
        (2) Purchase tickets and ride a scenic or historic railroad. Under
        supervision, photograph the equipment and discuss with your counselor
        the historic significance of the operation.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10302 mb-requirement-id-10305">
        (3) Locate the website of four rail historical groups, then find
        information on the history of the rail preservation operations and
        purpose of each group. Talk with a member of one of the groups and find
        out how you might help.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10302 mb-requirement-id-10306">
        (4) Plan a trip by rail between two points. Obtain a schedule and
        explain when the train should arrive at two intermediate points.
        Purchase the tickets and make the trip. Explain to your counselor what
        you saw.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
</div>
